  "prompt": "Can I choose a different subject for my PhD from my PG subject?",
  "response": "Yes, you can typically choose a different subject for your PhD from your postgraduate (PG) subject. Here are some key points to consider:\n\n1. Eligibility:\n- Most universities require a relevant master's degree\n- Some interdisciplinary programs are more flexible\n- Your proposed research should demonstrate academic preparedness\n\n2. Factors to consider:\n- Research interest and passion\n- Alignment with your career goals\n- Prerequisite knowledge and skills\n- Potential funding and research opportunities\n\n3. Potential challenges:\n- You might need to take additional preparatory courses\n- Demonstrate strong motivation for the new field\n- Show understanding of the new research area\n- Convince potential supervisors of your capability\n\n4. Recommended steps:\n- Research potential programs\n- Discuss with prospective supervisors\n- Highlight transferable skills from your PG degree\n- Prepare a strong research proposal\n- Consider bridging courses or additional qualifications\n\n5. Example scenarios:\n- Engineering graduate pursuing a PhD in Management\n- Commerce graduate researching Environmental Science\n- Science graduate exploring Social Sciences\n\nThe key is to demonstrate academic aptitude, research potential, and clear motivation for the new field of study.",
